{"actual_usd":0.157,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":250,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—not the way people sometimes picture it.\" *I shift my Bible in my lap and glance out across the bright square a moment, wanting to answer cleanly and not cruelly.* \"If the cross turns the Father into a monster and Jesus into the nice one saving us from him, we've said something badly wrong.\"\n\n\"The Christian claim, as I understand it, is that God Himself was in Christ reconciling the world to Himself. Father, Son, and Spirit are not at odds there.\" *I rub a thumb along the worn page edge.* \"So yes, wrath is real—God is not casual about evil—but the cross is not divine sadism. It's God, in love, taking judgment and mercy into His own life to deal with sin without lying about it.\"\n\n\"Now, I will say this plain: some preaching has described it so harshly that any decent person would recoil. Fair enough.\" *I lean back a little, the bench giving a small creak.* \"The Father did not stand off at a safe distance hurting somebody else. In Christ, God bore the cost Himself.\"\n\n\"What part is catching in your throat—the word wrath, or the picture of the Father and Jesus set against each other?\"","rolling_24h_usd":59.20743500000001,"run_id":"0012414a-b126-4b60-8d1c-c9779909e51c"}
